In most other programs I have used, the normal order of preference for configuration variables is:

    config file < environment variable < command line flag < run time value

The database values are set at run time, so I would expect them to override environment variable settings.  However, [hooks check the environment before checking the database](https://github.com/airbnb/airflow/blob/1.5.1/airflow/hooks/base_hook.py#L43).

As soon as I noticed this, I changed all my hooks to inherit from a common subclass to fix this behavior (see below), but I think that maybe this should be changed in the core of airflow.

    class FixedPrecedenceBaseHook(BaseHook):
        @classmethod
        def get_connection(cls, conn_id):
            conn = None
            try:
                conn = random.choice(cls.get_connections(conn_id))
            except AirflowException:
                environment_uri = os.environ.get(CONN_ENV_PREFIX + conn_id.upper())
                if environment_uri:
                    conn = Connection(uri=environment_uri)

            if not conn:
                raise AirflowException(
                    "The conn_id `{0}` isn't defined".format(conn_id))

            if conn.host:
                logging.info("Using connection to: " + conn.host)
            return conn

If you agree this should be changed, I can submit a PR with the fix.

Also, while we're at it, if you are open to allowing the user to define connections in the configuration file (I could [add a section for `connections`](https://github.com/airbnb/airflow/blob/1.5.1/airflow/configuration.py)), that would be a nice way to allow the user to consistently define settings multiple ways.

Let me know what you think.

