Example reproducer:
```
from nupic.bindings.algorithms import TemporalMemory

tm = TemporalMemory()
tm.compute(set(), True)
```

The cause seems to be an unchecked cast in https://github.com/numenta/nupic.core/blob/master/src/nupic/bindings/algorithms.i#L1674

```
  inline void compute(PyObject *py_x, bool learn)
  {
    PyArrayObject* _x = (PyArrayObject*) py_x;

    nupic::UInt32  len = (nupic::UInt32)PyArray_DIMS(_x)[0];
    nupic::UInt32* data = (nupic::UInt32*)PyArray_DATA(_x);

    self->compute(len, data, learn);
  }
```

This code assumes its argument is a PyArrayObject (which is a numpy array, AFAICT: http://docs.scipy.org/doc/numpy-1.10.0/reference/c-api.types-and-structures.html#c.PyArrayObject)


For reference, I ran into this when comparing the performance of the C++ TemporalMemory bindings with FastTemporalMemory (fast_temporal_memory.py) and TemporalMemory (temporal_memory.py). When switching out implementations (they have essentially the same interface) I ended up passing a python `set` (which is what the python versions expect) instead of a numpy array.

Looking around `algorithms.i`, it seems that unchecked casts of this sort are pervasive, so I'm just generically calling this bug "bindings segfault due to missing argument checking" instead of something specific to TemporalMemory::compute.

